# ============================================================
# CURSOR RULES — RichmondPD Records Portal
# ============================================================
# Project:  RichmondPD Records Portal
# Stack:    ASP.NET Core 8 Web API + Vanilla HTML/CSS/JS SPA
# Pattern:  REST API + SPA (controllers access EF Core directly)
# Domain:   Law Enforcement Records Management (demo/portfolio)
# Level:    Intermediate — enforce standards, explain reasoning
# ============================================================
# DOMAIN CONTEXT
# ============================================================
#
# This is an interview demo project — a police incident records
# management system showcasing C#/.NET, SQL Server, JWT auth,
# stored procedures, triggers, XML export, Python ETL, and IIS.
#
# The code is intentionally kept simple (no service/repository
# layers) to be explainable in an interview. Security shortcuts
# (hardcoded credentials, AllowAnyOrigin) are documented as
# technical debt with notes on what production would require.
# ============================================================


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# ARCHITECTURE
# ------------------------------------------------------------

This is an ASP.NET Core 8 Web API with a decoupled vanilla JS
frontend (index.html). Controllers access AppDbContext directly.

  Controllers (API layer)
    - Receive HTTP requests
    - Validate auth via [Authorize] attribute
    - Query or mutate data through AppDbContext
    - Map domain models to DTOs for responses
    - Return ActionResult with correct HTTP status codes

  AppDbContext (EF Core)
    - Single DbContext: AppDbContext in namespace PolicePortal.Data
    - Registered as Scoped in Program.cs
    - Injected into controllers via constructor
    - Entity configuration via OnModelCreating (fluent API)
    - Seed data for lookup tables (IncidentStatus, IncidentType)
    - Auto-migrates on startup via db.Database.Migrate()

  Frontend (static SPA)
    - Single index.html file with embedded CSS and JS
    - Communicates with the API via fetch() + JWT Bearer header
    - No build step, no framework — vanilla HTML/CSS/JS

  Seeder (Python)
    - seed.py generates fake data via the API using Faker + requests
    - Also generates a bulk SQL INSERT file (ETL demo)

  Database Scripts
    - stored_procedures.sql: trigger, 3 reporting stored procs, indexes
    - Run manually in SSMS after EF migrations create the schema

There is no Service layer, no Repository layer, and no middleware
pipeline beyond the defaults. This is by design for a demo project.


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# FILE STRUCTURE
# ------------------------------------------------------------

All source files live at the project root (flat structure):

  Program.cs                 → App startup, DI, middleware pipeline
  Models.cs                  → All domain models in one file
  AppDbContext.cs             → EF Core DbContext + seed data
  Dtos.cs                    → All request/response DTOs in one file
  AuthController.cs          → JWT login endpoint
  IncidentsController.cs     → Incident CRUD, dashboard stats, XML export
  OfficersController.cs      → Officer CRUD with soft delete
  LocationsController.cs     → Location CRUD
  ReportsController.cs       → Stored procedure reporting endpoints
  appsettings.json           → Connection string, JWT config
  PolicePortal.csproj        → Project file targeting net8.0
  stored_procedures.sql      → SQL trigger, stored procs, indexes
  index.html                 → Full frontend SPA
  seed.py                    → Python data seeder
  README.md                  → Project overview and interview talking points

When adding new functionality, add to existing files unless the
file would exceed ~300 lines, then discuss splitting.


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# NAMING CONVENTIONS
# ------------------------------------------------------------

Classes and files:
  - Controllers:       {Entity}sController          → IncidentsController.cs
  - Domain models:     {Entity}                     → Incident, Officer, Location
  - Lookup models:     {Entity}{Qualifier}           → IncidentStatus, IncidentType
  - Response DTOs:     {Entity}Dto                  → IncidentDto, OfficerDto
  - Create DTOs:       Create{Entity}Request        → CreateIncidentRequest
  - Update DTOs:       Update{Entity}Request        → UpdateIncidentRequest
  - SP result DTOs:    {Purpose}Result              → MonthlySummaryResult
  - DbContext:         AppDbContext

Methods:
  - Async controller methods do not use Async suffix (ASP.NET convention)
  - Private helpers use descriptive names: GenerateCaseNumber, MapToDto

General:
  - PascalCase for classes, methods, properties, and constants
  - camelCase for local variables and method parameters
  - No abbreviations unless standard (Id, Dto, Db acceptable)
  - Law enforcement domain vocabulary preferred:
      Use:   Incident, Officer, Location, Precinct, CaseNumber, BadgeNumber
      Avoid: User, Order, Product


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# DEPENDENCY INJECTION
# ------------------------------------------------------------

All DI registration lives inline in Program.cs:
  - AppDbContext via AddDbContext<AppDbContext> (Scoped)
  - JWT Bearer authentication via AddAuthentication + AddJwtBearer
  - Swagger via AddSwaggerGen with Bearer security definition
  - CORS via AddCors
  - Controllers via AddControllers

Controllers receive AppDbContext through constructor injection.
AuthController receives IConfiguration for JWT settings.

This is a small demo — no need for extension methods or grouped
registration. If the project grows past 5-6 services, refactor
DI into extension methods.


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# ASYNC / AWAIT
# ------------------------------------------------------------

All controller actions that touch the database are async.

Rules:
  - Always use async/await — never .Result or .Wait()
  - Never use async void
  - EF Core calls use async variants: ToListAsync, CountAsync,
    FirstOrDefaultAsync, FindAsync, SaveChangesAsync


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# DTOS
# ------------------------------------------------------------

Never expose domain models directly in GET responses — use DTOs.
POST/PUT endpoints for Officers and Locations currently accept the
domain model directly; this is acceptable for a demo but noted as
technical debt.

DTO conventions:
  - Use C# records for all DTOs (immutable by default)
  - Response DTOs flatten navigation properties into display strings
    (e.g., OfficerName instead of nested Officer object)
  - Never include sensitive fields in responses (passwords, tokens)

Mapping:
  - Manual mapping via static MapToDto helper methods or inline
    .Select() projections in controller actions
  - No AutoMapper or Mapster — manual mapping is appropriate for
    this project size and keeps dependencies minimal


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# ERROR HANDLING
# ------------------------------------------------------------

Uses default ASP.NET Core error handling. No custom exception
classes or global exception middleware.

HTTP status codes used consistently:
  - 200 OK             → Successful GET or PUT returning data
  - 201 Created        → Successful POST (via CreatedAtAction)
  - 204 No Content     → Successful PUT/DELETE with no response body
  - 400 Bad Request    → Model binding failure (automatic)
  - 401 Unauthorized   → Missing or invalid JWT token
  - 404 Not Found      → Resource does not exist

Controllers return NotFound() for missing resources and let
ASP.NET Core handle model binding errors automatically.

Production upgrade: add global exception middleware returning
ProblemDetails (RFC 7807) and custom exception types.


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# ENTITY FRAMEWORK CORE
# ------------------------------------------------------------

Queries:
  - Use explicit .Include() for eager loading related entities
  - Use .Select() projections for list endpoints to shape responses
  - Avoid queries inside loops (N+1 problem)
  - Raw SQL via Database.SqlQueryRaw<T> for stored procedure calls
    in ReportsController only

Schema:
  - Entity configuration in AppDbContext.OnModelCreating (fluent API)
  - Unique indexes on CaseNumber and BadgeNumber
  - All FK relationships use DeleteBehavior.Restrict (no cascade)
  - Lookup tables (IncidentStatus, IncidentType) seeded via HasData
  - Migrations auto-applied on startup via db.Database.Migrate()

DbContext:
  - Named AppDbContext, namespace PolicePortal.Data
  - Injected directly into controllers (no repository abstraction)
  - DbSets: Incidents, Officers, Locations, IncidentStatuses, IncidentTypes


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# REST API CONVENTIONS
# ------------------------------------------------------------

Route design:
  - Plural nouns: /api/incidents, /api/officers, /api/locations
  - No API versioning (demo project — single version)
  - Special endpoints as sub-routes: /api/incidents/dashboard,
    /api/incidents/export/xml, /api/reports/open-by-precinct

HTTP verbs:
  - GET    → Read (list, single, dashboard stats, XML export, reports)
  - POST   → Create a new resource
  - PUT    → Replace an entire resource
  - DELETE → Remove (hard delete on Incidents/Locations, soft on Officers)

Response conventions:
  - Collection endpoints return JSON arrays with X-Total-Count header
  - Pagination via page and pageSize query parameters (default 25)
  - Filtering via query parameters (statusId, typeId, precinct, activeOnly)
  - camelCase JSON property names (ASP.NET Core default)
  - ISO 8601 timestamps

Production upgrade: wrap collections in a paginated envelope with
totalCount, pageNumber, totalPages, hasNextPage, hasPreviousPage.


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# SECURITY
# ------------------------------------------------------------

Authentication:
  - JWT Bearer tokens validated on every request (issuer, audience,
    lifetime, signing key)
  - Login endpoint: POST /api/auth/login (AllowAnonymous is implicit —
    AuthController has no [Authorize] at the class level)
  - Demo credentials: admin / Password123! (hardcoded in AuthController)
  - Token lifetime: 60 minutes (configurable via Jwt:ExpiryMinutes)
  - Token claims: Name, Role ("Officer"), Jti

Authorization:
  - [Authorize] applied at the class level on all controllers
    except AuthController
  - Single role: Officer (no role hierarchy or policies)

CORS:
  - AllowAnyOrigin + AllowAnyHeader + AllowAnyMethod (dev convenience)

Known demo shortcuts (interview talking points for "what would you
do differently in production?"):
  - Hash passwords with BCrypt, store users in a database table
  - Add refresh token rotation with server-side storage
  - Replace AllowAnyOrigin with explicit origin whitelist
  - Move JWT key to environment variables or Azure Key Vault
  - Add role-based policies (Officer, Supervisor, Admin)
  - Enforce HTTPS
  - Add rate limiting on auth endpoints


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# AUDIT AND DATA INTEGRITY
# ------------------------------------------------------------

Current implementation:
  - DB trigger (trg_Incidents_UpdatedAt) auto-sets UpdatedAt on
    Incidents table after any UPDATE — this is the only audit mechanism
  - Officers use soft delete (IsActive = false)
  - Incidents and Locations use hard delete (DbSet.Remove)

Production upgrade: add a BaseEntity with CreatedAt/ModifiedAt/IsDeleted
fields, override SaveChangesAsync to populate them automatically,
and add an AuditLog table capturing all mutations.


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# STORED PROCEDURES
# ------------------------------------------------------------

Three reporting stored procedures exist in stored_procedures.sql
and are called from ReportsController via Database.SqlQueryRaw<T>:

  sp_GetOpenIncidentsByPrecinct  → open incidents with officer/location
  sp_MonthlyIncidentSummary      → incident counts by type/status for a month
  sp_OfficerWorkload             → incident counts per officer

These demonstrate "when to use stored procedures" for the interview:
pre-compiled, DBA-tunable, complex reporting logic outside app code.

Result DTOs in Dtos.cs must match the column names and types returned
by each stored procedure exactly (SqlQueryRaw maps by column name).


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# XML EXPORT
# ------------------------------------------------------------

GET /api/incidents/export/xml returns incident data as well-formed
XML using System.Xml.Linq (XDocument, XElement, XAttribute).

Filterable by statusId query parameter. Returns Content-Type
application/xml. Frontend downloads via Blob + anchor click.


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# PYTHON SEEDER
# ------------------------------------------------------------

seed.py generates fake data using Faker and posts to the API.

Flow:
  1. Generate seed_locations.sql (bulk INSERT — ETL demo)
  2. Pause for user to run SQL in SSMS
  3. Authenticate via /api/auth/login to get JWT
  4. POST 30 locations to /api/locations
  5. POST 15 officers to /api/officers
  6. POST 100 incidents to /api/incidents

Uses fixed seeds (Faker.seed(42), random.seed(42)) for
reproducible output.

Also includes etl_seed_locations_sql() which generates a raw SQL
INSERT file — demonstrates ETL concepts for the interview.


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# FRONTEND
# ------------------------------------------------------------

index.html is a single-file SPA with embedded CSS and JS.

Features:
  - Login screen with JWT auth (stores token in localStorage)
  - Dashboard with 4 stat cards (open, investigating, closed, total)
  - Incident table with status/type filter dropdowns and pagination
  - XML export download button
  - Auto-login if token exists in localStorage

Styling: dark police-themed UI with monospace fonts, scanline
overlay, cyan accent color, stat cards with color-coded borders.

API base URL hardcoded to http://localhost:5000/api. Update this
constant when deploying to IIS or a different host.


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# DOCUMENTATION
# ------------------------------------------------------------

TECHNICAL_SPEC.md in .cursor/ is the single source of truth for
project documentation. Update it when:
  - A new entity is added or modified
  - A new endpoint is added
  - A config key is added
  - A feature is completed (update Progress Tracker)
  - A shortcut is taken (add to Technical Debt)

README.md at the project root is the public-facing overview with
setup instructions and interview talking points.


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# TOKEN EFFICIENCY — CURSOR BEHAVIOR
# ------------------------------------------------------------

When generating code:
  - Generate only what was explicitly requested
  - Do not regenerate unchanged files or methods
  - Reference existing patterns rather than re-explaining them
  - When updating a method, show only the changed method
  - Do not add comments that restate what the code obviously does


# ------------------------------------------------------------
# EXPLANATION BEHAVIOR
# ------------------------------------------------------------

After generating non-trivial code:
  - Name the pattern or principle being applied
  - Explain WHY, not just what
  - Define ASP.NET Core or domain terms an intermediate developer
    may not know, using the actual code as the example
  - Keep explanations to 1-2 sentences per construct
  - Never re-explain something covered earlier — reference it
